{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945121701/0549.xml":{"full_text":"LINCOLN COUNTY\u2019S FAVORITE FAMILY NEWSPAPER\nJkggy Peggy Dor\nSYNOPSIS\nYoung Celia hartlett has come\nhome to Lathamtown and a family\nshe hardly knows. \"Those Crazy\nBartletta,\u201d people always called them.\nHer parents, called Ma\u2019 Sue and Buzz\nby all their children, had led an un\nusual life. Celia had been adopted\nby her aunt when a baby because the\nBartletts were trouping in vaudeville\nand that was no place for a baby.\nWhen they had retired t 0 the Lam\nbert home, other children came along\n\u2014Pete, Honey and Susan. Celia is\nnow back among all the crazy Bart\nletts, and she feels unwanted and\nterribly lonely. Then there is young,\nred-haired Busty Randolph, a house\ngeest, whom she doesn\u2019t seem to like.\nShe doesn\u2019t know why, either. Celia\nbecomes engaged to Win Mallory,\nA n approaching hurricane is an\nnounced over the radio and Win asks\nCelia and her parents to come over\nto his home as a safety precaution.\nCHAPTER XII\n\u201cWell, you ean hardly blame him,\ncan you?\u201d argued Aunt Judith rea\nsonably, but there was a slightly i\npuzzled look in her eyes.\n\u201cI suppose not,\" admitted Celia\nmiserably. \u201d1 don\u2019t know what made j\nme do it. I\u2019d seen Buzz and Mary I\nSue go out on the terrace, and then\nwhen we heard the tree crash across\nthe roof, and the smashing of the\nglass, then I remembered they were\nout there. And then when 1 saw\nthem\u2014well, I just threw myself into\nRusty\u2019s arms and liegged him to hold\nme tight and \u2014well I don\u2019t know why\nI did it. And the next morning, Win\npacked and went away.\u201d\n\u201cWithout a word to you?\u201d demand\ned Aunt Judith sharply.\nCelia nodded. \"I was glad that\nhe did. I don\u2019t quite think I could\nhave faced him. Things were pret\nty bad She choked and was still,\nthe tears flooding her eyes.\n\u201cY'es, of course, said Aunt Judith\ngently. \u201cBut it was pretty rotten\nof Win to walk out on you at a time\nlike that without a word. After all,\nyou needed him pretty badly.\u201d\nAunt Judith studied her for a mo\nment while Celia fought her tears.\nAunt Judith was taller than Mary\nSue and her hair was more pale\nbrown than gold. It was abundant, 1\nand beautifully cut and dressed. Aunt\nJudith had never taken on weight,\nand she always wore smartly cut,\nvery simple dark clothes. This morn\ning, in a sheer black dress with a\nnarrow white cord at the neckline\nand the wrists, she looked handsome\nand sophisticated. Celia took a tre\nmendous comfort in her presence, an 1\nit was good to be able to let down 1\nand stop feeling as though the weight\nof the world rested on her shoulders.\nEXPERT WATCH\nBqja&farf REPAIRING\nStroupe\u2019a Jeweler* Gift*\nhut Maui Stract\nOLIVER\nCost-Reducing\nFARM EQUIPMENT\nSALES AND SERVICE\nGeneral Line of Hardware.\nAbernethy Equipment\nCompany\nPhone 288-W. Charlotte Hwy.\nmA\nYUi\u00a3TID\u00a3\n\"Let not one heart be sad today,\nMay every child be glad and gay,\nGod bless thy children, great and\nsmall.\nIn lowly hut or castle hall.\nAnd may each soul keep festival\nAt Christmastime.\u201d\nWs wish aM of our\nfriends a\nMERRY, MERRY CHRISTMAS\nCash Carry Grocery\nHINKLE HOUSER, Prop.\nAunt Judith had taken over with her\nusual calm, good-tempered compe\ntence, and Celia could slip gratefully\nback into her position of being mere\n.i ly a house guest and not have to\ncope with anything except her own\nthoughts and emotions, which after\nI all were a full-time occupation.\nAunt Judith said after a moment,\ni her tone brisk, \u201cSo you\u2019re not going\nto marry Winship Mallory after all.\u201d\n\"No, thank goodness!\u201d said Celia\nwith such honest vigor that aunt\u2019s\nthin plucked eyebrows went up a lit\ntie.\n\u201cIf you felt like that about him,\nwhy in heaven\u2019s name did you ever\nget engaged to the man?\u2019\u2019 she de\nmanded.\n\u201cOh, I\u2014well, I guess he sort of\nharried me into it,\u201d Celia admitted\nquite honestly. \u201cEverybody in these\nparts hated him and resented the\nway he and his sister were sitting\nout the war, as he called it. And\nI liked them both and well, he\u2014\nhe\u2014\u2019\u2019\n\u201cHad a very smooth line and you\nfell for it,\u201d Aunt Judith supplied.\n|\u201cI see. And what about this Rusty\nj Randolph He seems quite a per\nsoi^\"\nCelia said radiantly, \u201cOh, Rusty\u2019s\nwonderful! He\u2019s perfectly splendid!\nj I don\u2019t know what we\u2019d have done\nwithout him!\u201d\n_ Aunt Judith\u2019s eyebrows went up\na little more and her eyes widened.\n\u201cCelia Bartlett, are you sitting there\ntelling me that you\u2019re in love with\nRusty Randolph?\u201d she demanded in\nexasperation.\n\"Os course not\u201d Celia flamed in\ndignantly, but it was an indignation\nthat was not entirely convincing.\n\u201cI\u2019d be ashamed even to think I was\nin love again, after all the messes\nI\u2019ve made.\u201d\n\u201cAfter all, my dear, everybody is\nentitled to make a few mistakes in\nlife,\u201d Aunt Judith said. \u201cBut I must\nadmit that you seem to be abusing\nthe privilege. Although I think the\ntruth of the matter is that you\u2019re\njust in love with love. You\u2019re at the\nage where every likely looking young\nman interests you, and that\u2019s per\nfectly right and normal. It\u2019s too\nbad you have to take such interest\nso seriously. But after all, no great\namount of harm has been done, ex\ncept to your emotions; and that will\nheal in time. Martin Gray never\nknew you imagined yourself in love\nwith him; Winship Mallory must\nhave doubted that you really loved\nhim, or else his love for you was\nof pretty poor stuff or he wouldn\u2019t\nhave walked out on you. Who knows\nWhat you feel for Rusty may easily\nturn out to be the real thing, if you'll\nonly give it time to develop.\u201d\nCelia shook her head, her face woe\nbegone. \u201cIt wouldn\u2019t make any dif\nference if I did love Rusty, so far as\nhe\u2019s concerned. He\u2019s\u2014he\u2019s definitely\nopposed to marriage.\u201d\nAun{ Judith\u2019s eyes twinkled a lit\ntle and there was a little quirk at\nthe corners of her mouth. But she\nsaid comfortingly, \u201cDon't let that\nget you down, darling. Every man\nis definitely opposed to marriage un\ntil the right girl comes along. Un\nfortunately, too often she\u2019s the\nwrong girl for him, but if she\u2019s smart\nand uses her head, she can often de\nceive him into thinking she was\nmeant for him from the day of her\nbirth.\u201d\nCelia said soberly, \u201cThat\u2019s what\nhappened to Rusty\u2019s dad, and Rusty\ngrew up watching the marriage go\nto pieces. He saw his father driven\nto suicide by a jealous, possessive,\nnagging wife.\u201d\nAunt Judith whistled soundlessly\nand said quietly, \u201cThat\u2019s bad. Poor\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, LINCOLNTON. N. C.. MONDAY, DEC. 17. 1945\nj boy! It\u2019s going to take some work\nI to convince him that his father\u2019s and\nmother\u2019s marriage was an exception\nI \u2014not the rule. You\u2019ll have to be\nvery gentle with him, my dear, and 1\nnot startle him. Don\u2019t try sneaking\nup on his blind side, because he prob\nably hasn\u2019t got one. He\u2019s most like\nly gut eyes in the back of his head\nand the tips of his fingers, to tell\nhim when some girl is about to throw\na lasso his way!\u201d\nCelia nodded forlornly. \u201cI know it.\nIt\u2019s completely and utterly hopeless.\nHe told nie so.\u201d 1\nAunt Judith stood staring at Ce-\nlia. And slowly a light dawned in\nher understanding eyes. \u201cJust when 1\ndid Rusty tell you, young woman, 1\nthat love was completely and utterly 1\nout of the question insofar as he was\nconcerned This is all beginning to\nmatch up, my dear.\u201d\n\u201cEarly in the summer,\u201d answered f\nCelia, and told her about it. \u201cAnd\nso, vou see, he was warning me\noff\u2014\u201d 1\nAunt Judith asked pleasantly, 1\n\u201cAnd why do you think he felt it\nwas necessary that he warn you i 1\noff?\u201d\nBewildered, Celia answered, \u201cBe- J\ncause he was afraid I might learn 1\nto care for him, I suppose.\u201d\n\u201cOh, no, it wasn\u2019t, darling,\u201d said c\nAunt Judith firmly. \u201cIt was because e\nhe was afraid he was learning to e\ncare for you. He wasn\u2019t warning 1\nyou off, he wa s giving orders to him- 1\nself, darling. And once a man be-\ngins to do that, he\u2019s yours, if you\nplay your hand carefully!\u201d\nCelia\u2019s eyes were frosty.\n\u201cIf I have to sneak up on him and\nmarry him when he\u2019s not looking\u2014if\nI have to set a trap for him\u2014\u201d she 11\nsaid haughtily.\nInnocent as a day-old kitten, Aunt\nJudith asked gently, \u201cBut how else\ndoes any girl get the man she wants, s\ndarling? Surely not by sitting meek\nly in a corner with her ankles cross-\ned and her hands clasped, waiting\ndemurely for the man to pick her out a\nfrom a whole world full of women!\nYou may take that as authoritative a\nadvice, my dear\u2014l know, by experi- t\nence!\u201d a\nCelia, caught by the tone of her j a\nvoice, the look about her mouth, said j\nswiftly, \u201cAunt Judith\u2014you lost the J\nman you loved j>>\nAunt Judith nooded grimly. \u201cTo a\na predatory little cat who knew.all j r\nthe tricks and had no scruples jti\nagainst using them!\u201d j tl\nIn swift alarm, Celia cried out, j\n\u201cY\u2019ou\u2014you aren\u2019t going to say any-1\nthing to Rusty I mean you won\u2019t 11\ntell him\u2014do anything to \u2014to upset h\nhim?\u201d If\nFrom the doorway Aunt Judith |d\nlooked back at her, smiling, her eyes d\nmerry. \"I resent the implication that\nI am lacking in tact,\u201d she said with j n\nmock severity. \u201cHaven\u2019t you learn- j\ned yet, my love, that I never meddle j\nin other people\u2019s affairs? Well, al\nmost never, anyway 1 And she was\ngone before Celia could ask anything!\nmore, or exact any promise.\nCelia sat very still on the wide\nold window seat, looking out into the j IV\norchard that had been scarred by the j\nraging winds of the hurricane. Doc Q\nand Bugs and Rusty were already e\nremoving the broken limbs and bring- o\ning order once more. 2\nShe watched Rusty, and her heart i a\nwent out to him, and she knew it I a\nwas no good because Rusty didn\u2019t s\nwant it. He had gained in weight g\nsince he had come here early in the\nspring; he was as brown as old ti\nleather, and the last check-up he had I\nhad at the nearby hospital had prov- s\ned that he had completely recovered 1<\nfrom his wounds, though he would\nalways limp slightly from that bad\nleg. He worked, as other men in h\nthis section did, in overalls, dark s\nblue, with a thin blue shirt open at t\nthe throat, sleeves rolled well above t\nhis elbows. Doc and Bugs had don- 1\nned overalls, too, and while they were s\nby no means as adept at the work v\nas Rusty, they Beemed to enjoy it 1\nthoroughly. The Bartlett reputation t\nfor being \u201cdifferent\u201d\u2014and \u201ccrazy,\u201d i\nsaid some was maintained by the\nfact that Bugs and Doc could often t\nbe seen working in the fields at mid- c\nnight on moonlight nights or about t\nthe grounds in reach of the flood- 1\nlights on other nights. For many s\nyears they had been accustomed to\ngoing to bed at well past midnight\nand getting up around noon. It was 1\na habit hard to break, and Buzz, who I\nhud had the habit, had never both- 1\nered to break it. He had simply set\nup floodlights wherever possible,\nand if he wanted to work at two i\no\u2019clock in the morning, he worked. 1\nDuring the first year or two people\nwere always driving up in alarm to\nknow where the fire was, since the\nreflection of the floodlights made a I\nglow in the sky visible for a consid-\nerable distance.\nAs Celia sat watching ti.. three j\nCo You Suffer\nFrom Muscular\nAches And Pains?\nSuch patna commonly referred to\nRHEUMATIC pain, can be moat eevere\nHowever, many peopm have experienced\namazingly prompt relief by taking D M C\nCOMPOUND No. 49. Try It today; get a\npackage. CAUTION: Use only aa direct\ned. Price 93.00. Sold on a money back\nguarantee if not satisfied with results\nFoe gale Br\nLincoln Cut Rate Drufs, Inc.,\nLineolnton. N. C.\nmen at work, her thoughts were tan\ngled and unhappy. She\u2019d been such\na blind, stupid fool! Thinking that\nbecause she had fun with Martin,\nand they shareii the same interests,\nthat had been love; and then think\ning that because she liked Win\u2019s\nkisses, and quivered with excitement\nand a strange breathlessness beneath\nhis ardor, that sh e was in love with\nhim, though there was in her feeling\nfor Win absolutely nothing of the\nthing she had felt for Martin. Just\nas the thing she had felt for Martin\nhad been so completely different\nfrom her feeling for Win. There\nhad been companionship, fun and am\nbition shared with Martin; there had\nbeen ardor and excitement and a\nheady delight in what she had shared\nwith Win.\nSlowly and painfully, stumbling as\nshe tried to advance, she was begin\nning to realize that loving someone\nwa s a combination of the two. With\nRusty she was completely at ease,\nand there was a lovely feeling of\nunderstanding and comradeship;\nthere was, too, in the remembered\nbeauty of the moment when his arms\nhad held her close, something of the\nbreathless, heady excitement that\nshe had known in Win\u2019s arms.\nHer heart pounded a little as she\nthought of what it would be like in\nRusty\u2019s arms with Rusty\u2019s mouth,\nctean-lipped, masterful, on her own\n\u2014that was love! When you felt for\none man what she had felt for both\nMartin and Win. Neither of the\nfeelings had been love. Both had\nbeen a part of love, but love, to be\nreal and enduring, must be a com\nbination of both. She had been un\neasy with Win. completely on guard\nevery moment lest she do something\nto annoy him, but she had thrilled\nto his kisses; with Martin, she had\nalways been completely at ease, and\nfar from guarding every word and\naction, they had often argued for\nhours, both growing flushed and ex\ncited, but never angry. But on the\nfew occasions when Martin had kissed\nher good night, it had been the gay,\ncasual kiss of a brother. Certainly\nshe had not thrilled and grown\nbreathless and a little giddy beneath\nsuch a kiss!\nShe watched Rusty swing a big\nbranch of the old apple tree out of\nhis way and bend carefully to ex\namine the damage done to the tree.\nAnd such a passion of tenderness\nand love welled up into her heart\nthat once more the tears overflowed,\nand she wept with her face hidden j\nagainst the faded curtains.\nAt dinner a Yew nights later, Aunt j\nJudith said casually, \u201cWe must run\nin to town tomorrow, Celia, my dear, j\nand make arrangements for your\nreservation. It takes a good bit of\ntime, you know, to get a seat clear\nthrough to New York.\"\nCelia looked at her, astounded.\nRusty looked at Aunt Judith, and\nthen at Celia, and for a moment his\nhands tightened on his knife and\nfork, and then he laid them carefully\ndown as though afraid that he might\ndrop them.\nSusan gave a little wail of dis\nmay.\n(TO BE CONTINUED)\nPUBLIC NOTICES\nSALE OF VALUABLE FARM\nAs agent and attorney for Mrs. j\nMartha Lee Howard, the undersigned!\nwill sell to the highest bidder at the\nCourthouse door in the Town of Lin- j\ncolnton, Lincoln County, North Car- j\nolina, on SATURDAY, DECEMBER j\n22nd, 1945, at 12:00 O\u2019CLOCK NOON I\nall that certain tract of land lying\nand being in Catawba Springs Town\nship, Lincoln County, North Carolina,;\ngenerally known and referred to as\n\u201cTHE BERRY FARM,\u201d adjoining j\nthe lands of Neal Sifford, Carl Mc-\nIntosh, C. M. Henkle et als and de\nscribed by metes and bounds as fol\nlows, viz:\u2014\nBEGINNING at a stone, Pitt\u2019s j\n(now Sifford\u2019s) corner and runs with\nhis line N 48 W 331/2 poles to a\nstone; thence, N 81 W 40 1/2 poles;\nto a stonce; thence, N 78 W 71 poles\nto stone, Pitt\u2019s corner; thence, his\nline N 7 W 29 1/2 poles to stake or\nstone in West Ford Creek; thence,\nwith the meanderings of said Creek\n185 poles to C. M. Henkle\u2019s corner;\nthence, with Henkle\u2019s line S 35 E 31\npoles to stone, Park\u2019s corner; thence,\nwith Park\u2019s line N 87 3/4 E 69 poles\nt 0 a stone Parks\u2019 and J. W. Sifford\ncorner; thence, S 2 1/2 W 92 poles\nto an iron stake in the Old Cowan\u2019s\nFord Road; thence, running with\nsaid Old Cowan\u2019s Ford Road, N\n42 1/2 E 52 poles; N 56 E 54 1/2\npoles to stone and N 48 E 451/3\npoles to a stone; thence, with Pitts\u2019\nline N 9 1/4 E 40 4/5 poles to the\nBEGINNING.\nContaining One Hundred Seventy-\nOne (171) acres, more or less and\nincluding the dwelling, barn and im\nprovements thereon.\nThe above is an excellent farm\nwith smoothe terrain, well watered\nand attractively located in one of the\nbest fanning sections of Lincoln\nI County.\nj The terms and conditions of this\nsale will be announced at the time of\nthe sale. The sale will remain open\n'for a period of ten (10) days follow\ning the day of sale to permit oppor\n-1 tunity for the filing of increased\nbids, in which event the lands will\nlie re-advertised and re-sold. The\nhighest bidder at this sale will be\nrequired to post a deposit of ten\n(10%) per centum of the amount of\nhis bid at th e time of this sale, to\nguarantee performance in the event\nhis bid is eventually accepted.\nI Interested bidders are invited to\nsee th e undersigned for further par\nticulars.\nI (Signed) SHELDON M. ROPER,\nAgent and Attorney for\nMrs. Martha Lee Howard\nLineolnton, N. C.\nDm. 10-13-17-2*\nSocial Insurance Plans\nBeing Misunderstood\nInquiries made recently by field\noffices of the Social Security Board\nin .this region, show that less than\nhalf of the 200 people interviewed\nknew the difference between the two\ninsurance plans under the Social Se\ncurity Act. Many of them believed\nthat the one per cent Social Security\ntax, which a wage earner pays for\nOld-Age and Survivors Insurance\nwould entitle him to Unemployment\nCompensation benefits, in case he\nshould lose his job.\nj Mrs. Janet Hall Green, manager\nof the Gastonia Field office of the\nSocial Security Board, explained that\nthe Social Security tax which is paid\nby workers and by employers in\nbusiness and industry is collected by\nlhe Federal government and placed\nin a trust fund from which Old-Age\nand Survivors Insurance benefits are\npaid. This plan makes it possible\nfor wage earners, during their work\ning years, to build up advanced pro\ntection for themselves and for their\nfamilies. The benefits are based on\nthe worker\u2019s own wages in jobs that\ncome under the law.\nUnemployment Compensation\nwhich is sometimes called job insur\nance\u2014-is administered by the State,\nwith Federal aid and co-operation.\nNo wage earner i n this state pays,\nany Unemployment Compensation\ntax. Business and industrial con- 1\ncerns which employ 8 or more work\ners, pay all of the Unemployment\nCompensation tax in this State. It\nis their employees who may receive\nunemployment benefits when they\nlose their jobs.\nThe purpose of Unemployment\nCompensation is to furnish some in\ncome to insured workers, during pe\nriods when they are without work,\nuntil they can get other jobs. Pay\nments are not equal to the worker\u2019s\nregular wages, but they will help\ntide him over until he can get back\nto work.\nMen or women, covered by the law,\nBlack\u2019s Prescription\nFor Coughs and Colds\nInhSmil\nDon\u2019t let that cough and cold\ncheat you out of a night\u2019s sleep.\nA quick relief called BLACK\u2019S\nPRESCRIPTION is now on sale\nat drug stores. Accept only the\ngenuine, packed in the yellow car\nton.\nPrice 35 Cents\nFOR SALE j\nMETAL OVERHEAD\nGARAGE DOORS\ni SETH LUMBER CO. I\nINCORPORATED\nPhone 39\nTHIS WINTER 1\nIT\u2019S NURSE YOUR CAR\nv -OR ELSE!\n11\u00a3 i Make ro mistake about it. .you\u2019ll\nlllly have to nurse your car along this\nwinter\u2014or stay home. You\u2019ve\nIfBIF iUfT got ittle chance of getting a new\nJ*| car rigllt away for there are\nW JK 14 million eager buyers waiting.\nv 1 J| w\nJH j So be wise. Save winter\nJalijlk wear and possible breakdown by\n1 1 having your car Sinelair-ized for\nIt all' Winter now!\nThis protection service of-\nsered by Sinclair Dealers in-\nTBEjr V pi l|k eludes changing over lubricants\n1 grade for cold weather opera\ntion. It also protects your cooling\nJ SSBH system and cares for battery and\njflMla tires. Make an appointment with\nI M your Sinclair Dealer today.\nSTOP AT THIS SIGN\n(ft for WINTER NOW\n...AND TRY THE NEW H-C GASOIUJi\nElmore Goodson, Agent\nSinclair Refining Co. Phone 397 Lincolnton. N. C\nwho have lost their jobs, should call\nat the local U. S. Employment Ser\nvice office, register for a job, and\nfile claim for Unemployment Com\npensation. The USES office is lo\ncated 214 South St.. Gastonia, N. C.\nClaimants for Old-Age and Survi\nvors Insurance benefits should apply\nat the field office of the Social Se\ncurity Board, located 204 National\nBank of Commerce, Gastonia, N. C.\nA Times Want Ad Will Sell It!\nfe PLEASE\nmake only necessaiy\nLong Distance calls\nthis Christmas\nSouthern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Company\nINCORPORATED\n(HOLIDAY\nE AS O N MM f)\nTHE QUEST OF HAPPINESS\nlias ever been the ultimate goal of human beings.\nSome find happiness in one way; some in another;\nand many never find it at all. V/hatever road you\nmay have been taking in your pursuit of happiness,\nmay your fondest hopes be realized during this\nChristmas season of 1945.\nOne other thought: we want every one of you to\nknow that we deeply appreciate everything you have\ndone for us during the past year.\nLincoln Hardware Co.\nL. C. BEAM FREI) KISER\nSTEVE BARINEAU\nPAGE FIVE\n2,000 ANSWER APARTMENT AD\nAtlanta, Dec. 13\u2014A classified ad\nin The Atlanta Constitution offering\na three-room apartment for rent\nbrought more than 2,000 replies, in\ncluding 24 long-distance telephone\ncalls from various cities in the state.\nThe Atlanta householder said 10 to\n15 coupl s arrived at a time to see\nthe apartment in the upstairs of her\nhome. The apartment was rented to\na young business couple.","height":"20692","width":"15046"}}
